Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.440
BEN SPARKS: Let's say, you're in Britain
on a dual carriageway.

00:00:02.440 --> 00:00:05.400
I'm gonna try and draw this.
Two lanes, and we'll both go in this direction

00:00:05.400 --> 00:00:09.840
and there's a blue car on the left,
and it's going at 70 miles per hour

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:14.100
which is the legal limit on motorways
and dual carriageways in this country.

00:00:14.100 --> 00:00:15.380
BRADY HARAN: They're doing the right thing.

00:00:15.380 --> 00:00:16.980
BEN: Yeah, and so they should be.

00:00:16.980 --> 00:00:20.920
Trouble is, you could be doing the right thing,
and other people on the roads might not.

00:00:20.920 --> 00:00:23.579
There's a guy overtaking the blue car.
It's gonna be the red car.

00:00:23.580 --> 00:00:24.760
BRADY: It's always the red car!

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:26.560
BEN: It's always the red car, and he's going faster.

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:29.660
In fact, I'm gonna draw him in
at the moment he overtakes

00:00:29.660 --> 00:00:33.040
and he's going -- as I'm sure it's happened to me,
in the blue car I hasten to add

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:37.280
I've been in the blue car, and someone comes
barreling past me going at 100 miles an hour.

00:00:37.280 --> 00:00:40.520
Certainly it could happen,
whether it's on a motorway or dual carriageway.

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:43.840
Now, they're not going the same speed,
but there is a moment when they're neck-and-neck

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:47.760
and that's the moment I want to freeze time
and ask you about what happens next.

00:00:47.760 --> 00:00:50.800
Because at this moment when they're neck-and-neck,
they see in front of them a tree

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:54.540
or some barrier which is unexpected,
and so they both need to break

00:00:54.540 --> 00:00:57.480
and we're going to assume lots of things,
like is always the case with a mathematical question.

00:00:57.480 --> 00:00:59.620
We have to model it to keep it simple enough to answer.

00:00:59.620 --> 00:01:02.480
So the models here might be that,
let's assume have same cars.

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:05.180
Let's assume reaction times are not part of this.

00:01:05.180 --> 00:01:07.580
We could add those things in later
if we want to complicate the model.

00:01:07.580 --> 00:01:11.040
Let's assume they both slam on the brakes
at the same time, and they break at the same rate

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:14.940
and by the time he gets there,
the blue car has sort of just stopped in time.

00:01:14.940 --> 00:01:17.800
So that's the blue car, who's got smaller apparently...

00:01:18.380 --> 00:01:21.080
He has stopped with millimeters to spare,
which is good.

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:24.960
BRADY: So the blue car just,
just stops as it gets to the tree.

00:01:24.960 --> 00:01:28.140
BEN: No crash for the blue guy.
He slammed on the brakes just in time.

00:01:28.140 --> 00:01:31.640
What I'm gonna claim, it's obvious
that the red guy is in trouble.

00:01:31.640 --> 00:01:34.540
The red guy is moving quicker.
He brakes at the same time, at the same rate.

00:01:34.540 --> 00:01:37.800
I think he's definitely gonna crash. No one seems
to argue about whether the red guy's gonna crash.

00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:40.220
What's really crucial, and here's the puzzle for you

00:01:40.220 --> 00:01:42.300
is that, it matters what speed you crash at.

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:45.060
Right, if you crash at one mile an hour,
no one's gonna really worry.

00:01:45.060 --> 00:01:48.560
If you crash at a thousand miles an hour,
you're in trouble.

00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:52.700
Now, he's not gonna crash at thousand miles an hour.
He's gonna crash slower because he started braking.

00:01:52.700 --> 00:01:56.540
But, at what speed does he hit the tree?
And that's the puzzle.

00:01:56.540 --> 00:02:00.020
There's some intuition to get involved here,
there's also some maths to check it out

00:02:00.020 --> 00:02:02.240
and the answer is-- well, it surprised me.

00:02:02.500 --> 00:02:05.980
BRADY: # Do do do do-do do do #

